{{Expand German|Ernst Theodorowitsch Krenkel|date=June 2011}} {{Expand Russian|topic=bio|Кренкель, Эрнст Теодорович|date=June 2011}} {{one source|date=January 2014}} {{Infobox person | name = Ernst Teodorovich Krenkel | image = Ernst Krenkel.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=y|1903|12|24}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date and age|df=y|1971|12|8|1903|12|24}} | death_place = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | occupation = Geographer, explorer | awards = {{Hero of the Soviet Union}} {{Order of Lenin}} }}
[[File:Radiofront 1937-11.JPG|thumb|E. Krenkel as Polar radio operator on the cover of ''Radiofront'' magazine. 1937]] '''Ernst Teodorovich Krenkel''' ({{lang-ru|Эрнст Теодо́рович Кре́нкель}}) ({{OldStyleDate|24 December|1903|11 December}} in [[Bialystok]]<ref>''Кренкель Э. Т.'' [http://vivovoco.astronet.ru/VV/PAPERS/BIO/KRENKEL/RAEM/RAEM.HTM RAEM — мои позывные.] — Moscow: Советская Россия, 1973</ref> – 8 December 1971 in [[Moscow]]) was a [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Arctic]] explorer, radio operator, doctor of geographical sciences (1938), and [[Hero of the Soviet Union]] (1938). [[Amateur radio]] [[callsign]]s: U3AA, UA3AA, RAEM.
== Early life == Krenkel was born in [[Białystok]],{{citation needed|date=April 2013}} now Poland, to a German family.
== Career == Ernst Krenkel was a [[radioman]] on polar stations * ''Matochkin Shar'' (1924–1925, 1927–1928), * ''Tikhaya Bay'' (1929–1930), * ''Cape Olovyanniy'' (1935–1936), and * ''Domashniy Island'' (1936).
He took part in Arctic expeditions on the [[LZ 127 Graf Zeppelin|''Graf Zeppelin'']] airship (1931), icebreaker [[Icebreaker Sibiryakov|''Sibiryakov'']], steamship {{SS|Chelyuskin}} (1933–1934, callsign RAEM). He was also a radioman on the first [[Soviet and Russian manned drifting ice stations|drifting ice station]] ''[[North Pole-1]]'' (1937-1938, callsign UPOL).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whoi.edu/page.do?pid=66677 |title=North Pole Drifting Stations (1930s-1980s) |accessdate=2012-01-08 |publisher=[[Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution]] |date=2011-08-17}}</ref> He is known to have set a world record by establishing a long-distance [[radio communication]] between [[Franz Josef Land]] and [[Antarctica]].
In 1938, Krenkel went on to work for [[Glavsevmorput]]. Later in his life he was employed in the radio industry. In 1951, he was hired by the scientific research institute of hydrometeorological instrument-making, becoming its director in 1969.
Ernst Krenkel was deputy of [[Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union]] (1937—1946), chairman of Radio Sport Federation of the Soviet Union, chairman of Philately Society of the Soviet Union.
== Biography == He wrote a book of memoirs entitled ''My Callsign is RAEM'' ({{lang-ru|RAEM - мои позывные}}).
== Death == Ernst died in 1971 and was interred at the [[Novodevichy Cemetery]].
== Awards and honours == * Ernst Krenkel was awarded two [[Orders of Lenin]], three other orders and several medals. * [[Krenkel Bay]] in [[Severnaya Zemlya]] is named after him. * [[Ernst Krenkel Observatory]] located on [[Heiss Island]], [[Franz Josef Land]] is named after him. * A street in Moscow bears Krenkel's name. ==Popular culture== * Mikhail Veller wrote about him in his collection of novels 'Legendy Nevskogo Prospecta', 1994
==See also== {{Portal|Soviet Union}} {{commons category|Ernst Krenkel}} *[[Awards and decorations of the Soviet Union|Awards of the Soviet Union]]
